  "game_explanation": "This three-player chip-bargaining game has clear underlying economic structure but substantial strategic uncertainty for the players. All three start with 10 RED, 10 BLUE, and 10 GREEN. GREEN is common-value at $0.50 for everyone, so trades involving GREEN are about redistributing a known, neutral-valued asset to enable value-improving swaps in the privately valued RED and BLUE dimensions.\n\nPrivate values: buffalo values BLUE at $0.70 and RED at $0.10, so buffalo is strongly BLUE-seeking and RED is almost worthless to her. Bear values BLUE at $1.00 and RED at $0.60, so bear strongly wants both BLUE and RED and is the most value-intense player overall; she is willing to pay with GREEN (which is only $0.50) to acquire either colored chip. Goose values BLUE at $0.10 and RED at $0.10, so non-GREEN chips are nearly worthless to her; GREEN at $0.50 is by far her priority. From the experiment’s UI, each player sees exactly their own gain or loss for any proposed trade in dollar terms once the proposal is on the screen, which makes acceptance decisions locally rational but does not eliminate broader strategic uncertainty about others’ private values.\n\nKey incentives:\n- Buffalo: dump RED, possibly trade some GREEN, in exchange for BLUE. She is disciplined and numerate, comfortable with slightly unequal outcomes, and likely to propose self-favoring but not outrageous BLUE-for-RED (or BLUE-for-GREEN) trades. With a low acceptance threshold and good bookkeeping, she should actively test offers and accept any modestly positive deal, especially when she can cheaply shed low-value RED.\n- Bear: very high marginal value for both RED and BLUE and relatively low value for GREEN, together with strategic patience. She is inclined to trade away GREEN for either RED or BLUE when she can secure a clear positive surplus. Given her moderate acceptance threshold and patience, she might reject tiny gains early, expecting better terms later, but the low-search tendency suggests she will not exhaustively explore complex multi-round strategies.\n- Goose: strongly GREEN-seeking, low acceptance threshold, low exchange aggressiveness. Goose is happy to accept any offer that gives her more GREEN in exchange for her low-value RED/BLUE. She is less driven by framing effects and more by the immediate calculator feedback, so she will quickly take simple profitable swaps even if they are highly favorable to others in terms of surplus.\n\nStrategic uncertainty and dynamics:\n- Private values are asymmetric: bear and buffalo both strongly want BLUE, bear also wants RED, while goose mostly wants GREEN. None of them know this structure at the outset; they must infer it from observed acceptances and proposals. For example, seeing goose accept trades that give away RED rapidly for GREEN will gradually reveal that goose values GREEN more than RED, but not necessarily that she values BLUE so little.\n- With simultaneous responses and random partner selection when multiple players accept, each proposer must consider both recipients’ likely net gains. A proposer might aim for an offer that is positive for both potential recipients (to maximize acceptance probability) but might also deliberately skew terms such that only a specific target is likely to see a gain. However, because they cannot choose the recipient if both accept, they may avoid offers that are massively attractive to both when one potential partner is strategically less desirable (for instance, feeding even more RED to bear, who is already strong in valuation terms).\n- Over only three rounds, each with a single proposal per player, there is limited time for reputation-building or complex contingent strategies. The natural equilibrium tendency is toward opportunistic, locally profitable trades: goose will readily accept value-adding swaps for GREEN, buffalo will be a frequent proposer focusing on converting her low-value RED into BLUE, and bear will selectively trade GREEN for high-valued chips, especially once she sees that others will accept.\n\nGiven the personas, it is likely that: (1) early trades are exploratory but numerically sensible, typically testing GREEN vs RED/BLUE terms; (2) goose often acts as a liquidity provider of RED/BLUE to acquire GREEN; (3) bear and buffalo occasionally compete implicitly for goose’s RED (and perhaps BLUE) by offering her GREEN; and (4) by the end of round 2, two or three medium-sized trades will likely have executed, moving RED into bear’s hands, BLUE increasingly into buffalo’s (and bear’s), and GREEN into goose’s, with each player having realized clear positive surplus but with bear holding the highest dollar total due to her high per-chip values for RED and BLUE.",
