  "game_explanation": "All three players value red chips the most ($1 each) and green chips equally ($0.50 each). They differ only in blue values: otter=$0.40, peacock=$0.50, cat=$0.70. That means cat has the strongest relative preference for blue, otter the weakest, and peacock is in the middle. Efficient trades would move blue chips from otter to cat, and possibly from peacock to cat, in exchange for red (or occasionally green) flowing back the other way. Because values for red and green are common across players, most bargaining leverage comes from these blue-value differences and from inventory changes over time.\n\nStrategically, players know only their own values, so no one can see that others also value red at $1 and green at $0.50, nor that cat values blue much more. However, each proposal and response offers indirect clues: who is eager to trade blue away, who is willing to pay a lot of red or green for blue, etc. Otter is dispositionally less aggressive and relatively patient, tending to avoid sharp one-sided deals and being somewhat sensitive to apparent fairness and anchors. Peacock is deal-ready with a relatively low acceptance threshold, more willing to accept modest personal gains to lock in value. Cat is precise and disciplined about states and more prosocial, also with a low acceptance threshold and low exploitation caution, so she is likely to accept many offers that yield even small positive gains if they are clearly non-exploitative.\n\nUncertainty mainly concerns how much others value blue relative to red. A proposer might start with fairly conservative, seemingly fair terms (e.g., roughly equal dollar gains on both sides) rather than pushing extreme rates, because they cannot tell how desperate someone might be for blue. Over the three rounds, players can update beliefs: if cat repeatedly accepts blue-for-red trades at somewhat unfavorable chip ratios, others may infer cat likes blue more and adjust terms slightly against her. But with only three rounds and one proposal each per round, there is limited time for deep learning; most moves will be modest-margin trades that are obviously positive for both sides from the proposer’s perspective. Random tie-breaking when multiple players accept also adds risk: a proposer cannot target the preferred partner when both respond positively, so they may shape offers that are clearly attractive to one counterpart and less so to the other. Overall, the game is likely to see a few moderately generous, surplus-creating trades, with cat steadily accumulating blue and giving up some red and green, while otter (and to a lesser extent peacock) move in the opposite direction.\n\nBelow is a forecast of one complete, internally consistent playthrough: three rounds, with inventories updating after each accepted trade and players behaving in line with their incentives and personas.",
