  "game_explanation": "This three-player, three-round bargaining game features symmetric starting inventories (10 RED, 10 BLUE, 10 GREEN each) with common-value GREEN chips ($0.50 to everyone) and heterogeneous private values on RED and BLUE. Badger values RED and BLUE both at $0.80; Camel values RED at $0.60 and BLUE at $0.40; Squid values RED at $0.20 and BLUE at $0.60. All three value GREEN at $0.50. Efficient trades move RED chips away from Squid toward Badger (and somewhat toward Camel) and move BLUE chips away from Camel toward Badger and Squid. Because neither Camel nor Squid know others’ values, they must infer who likes which chip colors from observed offers. Badger is moderately disciplined and exploratory, likely to test a few self-favoring but not extreme trades and adjust to feedback. Camel and Squid are both relatively deal-ready with low acceptance thresholds, so they will often accept any proposal that yields a clear personal gain, even if the proposer keeps most of the surplus. Both also have strong numeracy and bookkeeping, so they accurately evaluate their own gains and losses. The main uncertainty is which bilateral relationships will form: Badger–Squid (trading Badger’s BLUE for Squid’s RED) and Badger–Camel (trading Badger’s BLUE for Camel’s RED, or Camel’s RED for GREEN/BLUE) are both potentially high-surplus. Another uncertainty is how fast players learn that Camel undervalues BLUE and Squid undervalues RED, making them natural counterparties for Badger. Given only three rounds and one proposal per player per round, players face a tension between experimenting to learn partner preferences and locking in safe, modest-gain deals. Random selection among multiple accepters also complicates targeting: a proposer cannot choose the recipient when both non-senders accept. Overall, we expect early feeler offers that are somewhat favorable to the proposer but still positive for at least one responder, followed by more targeted, mutually beneficial trades once some preference patterns are revealed, with most accepted trades generating small but clear gains for the responders.",
