  "game_explanation": "This three-player bargaining game features two privately valued chip colors (RED, BLUE) and one common-value color (GREEN). All players start with 10 of each color. GREEN is worth $0.50 to everyone, while RED and BLUE values differ: alligator values RED highest and BLUE lowest; otter values BLUE highest and RED lowest; tiger values RED high and BLUE low. Efficient trades move chips toward players who value them more (e.g., RED away from otter toward alligator or tiger, BLUE away from alligator or tiger toward otter). However, each player only knows their own values, so they must infer others’ preferences from observed proposals and acceptances across the three rounds. The one-shot nature (3 rounds × 3 turns = 9 moves) limits prolonged back-and-forth, but the proposer schedule is symmetric, so no one has a final-mover advantage.\n\nPersonas shape likely behavior. Alligator is prosocial, low-aggression, low search, and tolerant of unequal outcomes, with moderate bookkeeping: he is inclined to accept small positive gains and propose relatively generous trades, not aggressively exploit his RED advantage. Otter has very low acceptance thresholds, is exploration- and anchor-sensitive, and numerically strong: she is likely to accept many positive-expected-value offers (even modest ones) and experiment with different terms as proposer, though her offers may be framed to look attractive. Tiger is conciliatory, low-search but with good bookkeeping and somewhat higher minimum acceptance than otter: he tracks inventory and values carefully, likes fair or slightly favorable deals, and is less likely to take arbitrarily small gains than otter.\n\nThe main incentive tensions are: (1) identifying who values which chips most, (2) balancing surplus creation with bilateral division, and (3) anticipating random partner selection when multiple accept. Since responders see exact dollar gains or losses, dominated trades (negative value) will be rejected. Still, uncertainty about others’ values will lead to learning early and more targeted offers later. Alligator, valuing RED most, is naturally a RED seller only when getting high compensation, but as prosocial he may still offer RED for GREEN or BLUE at modest premiums. Otter, as a high-BLUE, low-RED player, should try to sell RED and buy BLUE or GREEN, and will very often accept trades that improve her total. Tiger, valuing RED almost as much as alligator and disliking low-value BLUE, is a natural buyer of RED and seller of BLUE or GREEN when terms are decent. Over the three rounds, we expect early, somewhat exploratory offers with more symmetric-looking ratios, then mild convergence toward patterns where RED flows to alligator/tiger, BLUE flows to otter, and GREEN serves as a neutral, safe settlement chip.\n\nThis forecast reconstructs one plausible complete path: players make simple, easy-to-evaluate offers; alligator and tiger avoid complex multi-step plans; otter’s low thresholds and search orientation generate several accepted trades; and by late rounds, players have partial but imperfect insight into each other’s likely valuations.",
