r others’ values from observed proposals and acceptance patterns, but in a short three-round game there is limited time to learn. Proposers must design offers that are: (1) profitable given their own values, (2) likely to be non-negative for at least one other player despite not knowing that player’s chip values, and (3) robust to the fact that if multiple others accept, the partner is chosen at random. Given all three are relatively tolerant of unequal splits and care more about securing a gain than enforcing fairness, the likely bargaining dynamics emphasize practical, surplus-creating trades using obvious win-win structure (e.g., Iguana trading blue for red, Zebra trading red for blue) rather than strategic holdout.\n\nAcross three rounds with each player proposing once per round, we can expect early offers to be somewhat exploratory in structure and conservatively favorable to the proposer. As players see who accepts which color directions (e.g., who jumps at red-for-blue or green-for-red), they refine later proposals. Because all players have low to moderate acceptance thresholds and a surplus calculator, several trades will likely be accepted, especially when they clearly move chips toward higher-value owners while leaving each side non-negative. However, some attempts may still fail when the proposer misjudges the counterpart’s relative values or offers too thin a margin for a risk-averse or patient responder.",
