pose modest, near-fair terms that visibly benefit themselves but also show a small gain to any recipient, and to accept decent positive-surplus offers rather than hold out aggressively. Lion is moderately guarded, medium exploration, with a somewhat higher rejection threshold: lion may decline very thin or ambiguous gains, especially if they sense the proposer might be exploiting private information. Tiger is numerate, low-search, and medium-selective: tiger prefers clear positive gains and closure over elaborate multi-round positioning, and is willing to trade when the calculator shows a clean, non-trivial benefit.\n\nStrategically, duck’s double-high valuation (red and blue both at $1) makes them a natural net buyer of both colored chips, especially from tiger (who values blue least) and somewhat from lion. Lion and tiger, both valuing red highly, are unlikely to sell red cheaply; both will view red as their main prize, especially from duck, whose behavior may reveal a strong willingness to pay for red. Since all value green the same at $0.50, green tends to be used as a relatively neutral payment medium, or as a safe store of value for players unsure about others’ private valuations of red/blue.\n\nGiven three rounds and one proposal per player per round, the game is short. Early in round 0, players are uncertain and may experiment with slightly conservative, exploratory offers to gauge willingness to trade. Because each proposal adjusts inventories immediately, a successful trade in an early turn can meaningfully reshape incentives later. The most likely patterns are: (1) early probing trades where duck tries to convert green into red/blue, or tests how cheaply they can buy red from lion or tiger; (2) lion and tiger proposing offers that attempt to acquire red from duck or sell blue to duck, while avoiding large green losses; and (3) in later rounds, if inventories have shifted, attempts to consolidate high-value holdings (duck trying to acquire more blue; lion 