  "game_explanation": "All three players start with 10 RED, 10 BLUE, and 10 GREEN chips. GREEN is common-value at $0.50 for everyone. BLUE is low-value at $0.10 for everyone. The only private-value difference is RED: for Badger and Peacock RED is $0.30, while for Unicorn RED is $0.50. This makes Unicorn the high-RED type who is willing to pay more for RED than the others, but nobody knows that ex ante; they only know their own values and the public ranges.\n\nFrom a surplus perspective, efficient trades move chips from lower-value to higher-value holders or convert low-value colors into high-value ones for a given person. Here, BLUE is worst for everyone, GREEN is best for everyone, and RED is intermediate for Badger and Peacock but equal to GREEN for Unicorn. That means: (1) everyone likes turning BLUE into GREEN; (2) Unicorn especially likes turning BLUE or GREEN into RED if the rate is favorable; and (3) Badger and Peacock are roughly indifferent between small shifts of RED and GREEN in value terms, but still care about not giving away too much surplus. Because GREEN is common-value and obviously valuable, and BLUE is obviously weak, GREEN↔BLUE trades will be benchmarked against a natural fairness anchor of about 1 GREEN ≈ 5 BLUE (both $0.50) if they tried to keep equal value. RED is noisier because players do not know others' RED values—only that RED is somewhere in a broad range.\n\nPersona-wise, Badger and Unicorn both have low acceptance thresholds and are relatively deal-ready, willing to accept small but positive gains rather than hold out. Peacock is more numerate and careful, with lower exchange aggressiveness and good bookkeeping, so is more likely to avoid dominated trades and to recognize when another player seems to value RED more. With only three rounds and one proposal each per round, there is limited time to learn types, but some inference can occur if someone repeatedly pushes to acquire RED or give up BLUE cheaply. Uncertainty comes from: (a) hidden private values for RED, (b) simultaneous accept decisions with random matching when both responders accept, and (c) the fact that every trade permanently changes inventories and future options.\n\nStrategically, senders want to construct proposals that are clearly profitable for themselves (as shown in their personal surplus calculator) while still giving at least one responder a modest positive gain. Given the personas, Badger and Unicorn are willing to propose modestly self-favoring trades hoping that someone bites, whereas Peacock aims for more balanced or clearly win–win offers, especially early. Because multiple acceptances lead to random partner selection, players cannot target a specific counterpart; they may prefer terms that are acceptable to at least one responder rather than finely tailored to a single one. Over three rounds, we can expect: early exploratory, relatively mild offers; some attempts to exploit inferred RED valuations (with Unicorn trying to accumulate RED, Peacock cautiously arbitraging BLUE into GREEN/RED, Badger opportunistically taking positive gains with little search); and occasional declines when a careful player sees a worse-than-fair exchange. Overall, the likely pattern is a small number of mutually beneficial trades that move GREEN or RED toward the players who visibly care more about them, along with a few declined turns where the surplus split is too lopsided or ambiguous.",
